"1145–1186","1175–1232":"1175–1232","1180–1215":"1180–1215","–Male":"Overleden","1120–Male":"1120–Overleden","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","1177":"1177","1232":"1232","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, West-Vlaanderen, België"},"en":{"1150–1187":"1150–1187","1145–1214":"1145–1214","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1175–1232":"1175–1232","1180–1215":"1180–1215","–Male":"Deceased","1120–Male":"1120–Deceased","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","1177":"1177","1232":"1232","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Gaineau</b>, itself a variant of <b>Ganeau</b>: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gagino</i>, from <i>gagin</i> ‘gain, win’. The surname <i>Gaineau</i> is very rare in France. Compare   Ganoe   and   Gunnoe  .","Slovak (<b>Gaňo</b>) and Polish: unexplained.","History: The Huguenot Étienne Gaineau or Gayneau from La Rochelle in Charente-Maritime, France, married Lydia Mestereau in La Rochelle in 1653, died in Staten Island, NY, in 1706. His name is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (as Étienne Gaineau or Ganeau or Geneau or Gano) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America (as Etienne Gaineau or Gano)."],"variants":[{"name":"Gunnoe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Mechelle, Pierre.","Variant of   Gano  , a surname of French origin."]},{"name":"Ganoe","meanings":["Variant of   Gano  , a surname of French origin."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Courtrai de Gand was born in 1150, in Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium, his father, Roger van Kortrijk I, was 30 and his mother, Sara de Frennes, was 31. He married Beatrix de Nevele in 1177. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1187, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1150–1187":"1150–1187","1145–1214":"1145–1214","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1175–1232":"1175–1232","1180–1215":"1180–1215","–Male":"Surnud","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","1177":"1177","1232":"1232","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fi":{"1150–1187":"1150–1187","1145–1214":"1145–1214","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1175–1232":"1175–1232","1180–1215":"1180–1215","–Male":"Kuollut","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","1177":"1177","1232":"1232","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fr":{"1150–1187":"1150–1187","1145–1214":"1145–1214","1150–Female":"1150–Décédée","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1175–1232":"1175–1232","1180–1215":"1180–1215","–Male":"Décédé","1120–Male":"1120–Décédé","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","1177":"1177","1232":"1232","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Kortrijk, West Flanders, Belgium":"Kortrijk, Flandre occidentale, Belgique","lifeSumm